Translate this JavaScript async/await pattern to idiomatic Hemlock. Hemlock uses `spawn()` to create tasks and `join()` or `await` to get results. There are no Promises - tasks are real threads.

```javascript
async function fetchData(id) {
  // Simulate async work
  return { id: id, value: id * 10 };
}

async function processAll() {
  const ids = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
  const promises = ids.map(id => fetchData(id));
  const results = await Promise.all(promises);

  let total = 0;
  for (const result of results) {
    console.log(`id=${result.id} value=${result.value}`);
    total += result.value;
  }
  console.log(`total: ${total}`);
}

processAll();
```

In Hemlock, use `spawn(fn, arg)` instead of Promise, and iterate to join each task.
